title: For Sale:  Nagant revolver &turk mauser
postcontent: 1- turk mauser :The 1903 is a large ring 1898 style Mauser but with a 1893 style small shank Barrel. According to Olson 200000 of these were made by Mauser in oberndorf between 1903 and 1905. When these were converted from their original 7.65 mm to 7.92 mm this is often called in 03 38. The receiver was slightly notched to easily allow loading of the slightly longer round. The bolt & action of the 1903 is also shorter than the actual 8mm Model 98. This is an intermediate length action and the bolt and magazine are 0.2 inches shorter than the standard length 98 action the receiver faces is 0.2 inches longer than a 98. other intimate intermediates include the M24 fn the Yugo Mausers and several South American contract rifles. This rifle would have had a pistol grip stock which is a change from the straight stalk of the 1893 the rear receiver bridge will also have a high hump the hump is there to handle the special clip and is also seen on the 1909 Peruvian. The Turks converted some Mausers that appear to be 1903s except for the missing hump. They even added a small piece to the receiver that supports their unique clips.Overall a very nice rifle with a shiny bore with strong grooves that should clean up nice. No cracks in wood or pitting in metal a very presentable rifle. ' these Turks are amazingly accurate for military surplus they might not be too pretty but they can definitely hold their own. I have 2 that I bedded the actions on swapped in a Boyd's bold trigger and added Mojo micro click sites. These are not full floated they are floated  two inches in front of the action to the nose caps. They provide a bit of up pressure and help to dampen Barrel harmonics. My turkey Mausers are 1.5 MOA rifles with Turk 154 grain Surplus period and MOA or better with Yugo m75 198 grain sniper ammo and closer to 2 inch MOA with Romanian 154 grain ball at 100 yards. $2602- Nagant Revolver 1943 refurb very clean nice shiny bore no issues great plinker in holster with lanyard and some ammo 300Reply by call or text is best REDACTEDJust letting go of a few items that have been in the safe for a very long time to help fund the application fee for my FFL.

title: For Sale:  Chinese M44 / T53
postcontent: After WWII the Soviet Union shared much of its weapons technology with its satellite countries, including the Mosin rifles and carbines. T53s were produced in the 1950s by China and other than minor differences these follow the same pattern as the post war Soviet M44s. 7.62 x 54RFor all intents and purposes this is the same rifle as any other M44 variant.It is very rare to find one of these rifles with all matching parts. This rifle has stamped all matching except for the butt plate. The rifle was made in 1955. The stock is in very good condition when compared to the usual condition of these rifles. It is worn and has signs of handling. The Chinese utilized a local wood that is known as CHU-wood. The CHU-wood was put to use as it was quite effective in standing up to so called "Jungle Rot." The wood was quite proficient in resisting moisture, so was a perfect choice for the environment of Asia.
